":"Earnings momentum","value":11.76,"unit":"% YoY","status":"ok","read":"Profit up 12% YoY \u2014 modest.","meaning":"Trailing-twelve-month net profit vs the year-ago TTM (and whether the YoY rate is rising = 'accelerating').","why_useful":"Improving, accelerating earnings tend to drive re-rating; falling profit warns of a deteriorating business.","why_it_can_fail":"TTM can be lumpy for cyclicals/one-offs; cross-check the multi-year trend on the Fundamentals tab."}]},"valuation":{"ok":true,"is_bank":false,"pe_now":41.1,"pe_percentile":43.0,"median_pe":47.7,"earnings_yield_pct":2.43,"pb":17.43,"ev_ebitda":30.22,"quality_score":66.0,"pat_cagr_5y_pct":23.7,"peg":1.74,"cheapness":{"status":"ok","read":"P/E at the 43-percentile of its 10-yr range \u2014 mid-range vs its own history."},"expectations":"At 41.1\u00d7 earnings for ~24% 5-yr profit CAGR, the market is paying \u22481.74\u00d7 growth (PEG). >2 = a lot already priced in; <1 = cheap if growth holds.","cyclical_caveat":null,"meaning":"P/E percentile = where today's price-to-earnings sits within the stock's own last-10-yr range (low = cheap vs its past). Paired with the Quality score and 5-yr profit growth so a cheap multiple is judged against business strength, not in isolation.","why_useful":"Cheapness only matters relative to quality and growth \u2014 a low P/E on a declining or peak-cyclical business is a trap, not a bargain.","why_it_can_fail":"P/E breaks for loss-makers / one-offs; for banks use P/B not EV/EBITDA; a multiple cheap vs history can stay cheap if the business has structurally de-rated."},"ownership":{"ok":true,"na":null,"holders":{"Promoter":{"periods":["Jun 2023","Sep 2023","Dec 2023","Mar 2024","Jun 2024","Sep 2024","Dec 2024","Mar 2025","Jun 2025","Sep 2025","Dec 2025","Mar 2026"],"values":[75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0,75.0],"latest_pct":75.0,"chg_1y_pp":0.0},"FII":{"periods":["Jun 2023","Sep 2023","Dec 2023","Mar 2024","Jun 2024","Sep 2024","Dec 2024","Mar 2025","Jun